Another step, and the corridor turned, passing through a narrow opening into the previous corridor. “Just as I had thought,”
Cody said. His satisfaction was cut short by a faint flicker in the light coming from the other corridor. Instinctively Cody
brought the pole sickle to bear in front of him, but he was too late to prevent the jaws of a second jackal from tearing at
his wounded shin. His agonized yelp was joined, oddly, by a few choice curses from what sounded like an irate shopkeeper.
Cody could not tell from where the other voice was coming, as his attention was focused almost exclusively on impending
bodily harm.
